Sensing the Living Wall: Sound, Image and Community Participation in a Situated Ecological Interface

Literature Review Draft
2.1 Smart Urban Interfaces and Situated Sensing

Smart city literature often describes urban environments as networked systems in which sensors, digital infrastructures and real-time data reshape how urban conditions are monitored and experienced. Early smart city frameworks define urban smartness through multiple dimensions, including governance, mobility, economy, people, living and environment (Giffinger et al., 2007). These models broaden the definition of the smart city beyond technology, placing digital systems within social, environmental and infrastructural processes (Giffinger et al., 2007). Smartness, in this sense, refers not only to the presence of digital tools, but to the capacity of urban systems, services and experiences to be reorganised through information, connectivity and responsiveness.

A situated reading of smart urbanism shifts attention from remote systems of observation to the ways digital technologies are embedded within everyday urban environments. The smart city is not only experienced through control rooms, administrative platforms or management dashboards. It also operates through distributed sensors, responsive surfaces, mobile interfaces, interactive installations and location-based media. Townsend argues that smart cities are shaped not only by top-down infrastructures, but also by the ways digital technologies are woven into everyday urban life and used by citizens, communities and local actors (Townsend, 2013). This view moves the smart city away from the image of a distant data system and towards a lived urban environment mediated by situated technologies.

Situated interaction reframes interaction as a bodily and spatial practice rather than a purely screen-based exchange. Dourish argues that interaction should be understood as embodied and embedded in social and material contexts, rather than as an abstract exchange between user and system (Dourish, 2001). Applied to smart urban environments, this means that interaction does not only happen after data has been collected and displayed. It can happen through approaching a surface, hearing a sound, touching an interface, noticing a change or responding to a local environmental condition. Smartness becomes something encountered in place, rather than only calculated at the level of the system.

This reading also changes the role of sensing within smart cities. In dashboard-oriented models, sensing often appears as a process of collecting data for management, prediction or control. In situated urban interfaces, sensing can also organise attention, awareness and local interpretation. Gabrys describes environmental sensing as a practice that does not simply measure the environment, but participates in producing environmental relations and forms of citizen engagement (Gabrys, 2016). Sensors may register environmental conditions, but they also shape how those conditions become noticeable, discussable and meaningful.

Media architecture and urban interaction design show how interfaces can become part of the built environment rather than detached screens. Digital displays, responsive façades, projection surfaces and interactive public installations do not simply present information; they alter how people move through, notice and participate in urban space (McQuire, 2008). An urban interface, in this sense, is not only a visual representation of data. It is a spatial and sensory situation that may invite people to stop, listen, touch, compare, record or respond.

The difference between a dashboard and a situated interface is central to this discussion. A dashboard translates the city into a visual field for overview and remote interpretation, while a situated interface brings digital interaction into the place where urban conditions are directly encountered. The former privileges abstraction, management and distance. The latter foregrounds proximity, encounter and perception. Environmental and ecological conditions are often experienced through local and bodily registers: sound, air, temperature, vegetation, texture, light and attention. A situated interface is better able to work with these registers because it does not remove environmental data from the place where it is felt.

Smart urban interfaces can be understood as devices for organising situated attention. The question is not only how urban data can be monitored, but how digital interfaces can make local environmental relations perceptible in place. This provides a useful framework for interactive systems installed in relation to existing urban surfaces. The interface is not a detached screen added after the fact; it becomes part of a sensory encounter with a specific site.

2.2 Greenness, Visibility and Ecological Perception

A situated interface depends on the material and visual qualities of the site in which it is placed. A green wall is not a neutral background for interaction. Its vertical surface, dense vegetation and visible greenness already make it a highly visual urban object. It functions as a sign of sustainability, environmental care and urban nature before any digital interface is added. In this sense, the green wall is not only a piece of green infrastructure, but also a visual image of ecological urbanism.

Green walls make urban nature visible by relocating vegetation onto architectural surfaces. Unlike parks or gardens, they attach greenery directly to the building envelope, turning plants into part of the façade. This gives the green wall strong symbolic power: sustainability becomes immediate, vertical and visually concentrated. Manso and Castro-Gomes describe green wall systems as vertical greening technologies associated with environmental benefits such as thermal regulation, air quality improvement, noise reduction and support for urban biodiversity (Manso and Castro-Gomes, 2015). These functions matter, but many of them are not directly perceptible through the visual surface of the wall.

The visible presence of green can make ecological value appear self-evident while leaving ecological processes difficult to perceive. A wall may look green while the processes that sustain it remain hidden: plant health, irrigation, seasonal change, humidity, maintenance, species interaction, sound and local forms of attention. The image of greenness reveals nature as an urban surface, but it can also conceal the dynamic relations through which urban ecology is produced and experienced. The wall may communicate sustainability visually without making its living processes available to perception.

Visual culture theory helps clarify why the green surface should not be treated as a transparent expression of ecology. Mitchell argues that images do not simply reflect reality; they organise how reality becomes meaningful (Mitchell, 1994). Mirzoeff similarly understands visual culture as a relation between image, viewer and social context, rather than as a simple act of seeing (Mirzoeff, 1999). Applied to green walls, this suggests that visible greenery is not just a direct presentation of nature. It is a visual construction that shapes how urban nature is recognised, interpreted and valued.

The gap between green image and ecological process becomes especially clear when environmental effects are considered. Thermal performance, plant stress, water use, acoustic effects and species presence are not always visible through vegetation alone (Manso and Castro-Gomes, 2015). A passer-by may see the wall as green without perceiving the environmental interactions taking place within or around it. Greenness can become a shorthand for sustainability, even when the ecological relations behind that image remain slow, hidden or difficult to interpret.

Sound complicates the visual reading of the green wall by introducing temporal and sensory evidence of ecological activity. Bird calls, insect sounds, rustling leaves or changes in ambient noise can suggest that the wall is not only a green surface, but part of a more dynamic sensory environment. Chion’s theory of audio-vision is useful here because it shows that sound and image do not simply sit beside one another; sound can change how an image is perceived, while an image can anchor and stabilise the meaning of sound (Chion, 1994). A visually static wall may be re-perceived as living or active when sound draws attention to processes that the surface alone does not show.

The relationship between sound and image in mediated environments is best understood as operational interdependence rather than natural inseparability. Sound provides immediacy, atmosphere and temporal presence, while image provides location, structure, recognition and memory (Chion, 1994; Manovich, 2001). A bird call heard near a green wall may be fleeting and difficult to identify. Once connected to a visual interface, location marker, species image, waveform, time record or environmental reading, the sound enters an interpretive structure. The image does not replace the sound; it gives the sound a spatial and temporal frame.

Urban soundscape research supports this relationship between sound, image and spatial interpretation. Aiello et al.’s Chatty Maps project constructs urban sound maps through geo-referenced image tags rather than direct microphone recordings (Aiello et al., 2016). This method shows that urban sound can be made publicly interpretable through the combination of photographs, metadata, categories and maps (Aiello et al., 2016). Soundscape knowledge is produced through mixed media rather than sound alone: images, tags and maps organise sound into forms that can be shared, compared and discussed.

The green wall can be understood as a sensory interface because it already operates as an image before any digital layer is added. An interactive system installed in relation to the wall does not need to visualise nature from nothing. It can work with the wall’s existing greenness while questioning the assumption that greenness is self-explanatory. By connecting the green surface to sound, time, environmental data and interaction, the interface can draw attention to what the visual image alone does not show.

Interaction shifts the wall from a static image of sustainability into a site of ecological perception. The interface can make hidden or temporary processes more available: changes in plant condition, variations in sound, species presence, microclimatic shifts or patterns of human attention. This movement from green surface to sensory ecology treats urban nature not as a finished visual symbol, but as something that must be listened to, interpreted and continually noticed.

2.3 Community Benefit and Participatory Ecological Sensing

Community participation changes environmental sensing from a technical process into a social process of noticing, interpreting and sharing. Smart urban interfaces are shaped not only by sensors, screens and environmental data, but also by the social relations through which data is produced and used. In environmental contexts, local residents often hold situated knowledge that cannot be fully captured by remote sensing or automated monitoring systems. Citizen science and participatory sensing literature shows that non-expert participants can contribute observations, photographs, recordings and local interpretations that expand the scope of environmental knowledge (Goodchild, 2007; Gabrys, 2016).

The concept of “citizens as sensors” reframes residents as active producers of environmental knowledge rather than passive users of urban technologies. Goodchild describes volunteered geographic information as a form of geographic knowledge produced by citizens using digital tools, where individuals contribute spatial observations that supplement formal datasets (Goodchild, 2007). This is particularly relevant to environmental sensing because ecological conditions are often uneven, local and temporary. Residents may notice small changes in sound, species presence, plant condition or atmosphere that are difficult for fixed infrastructures to capture.

Citizen science projects show how distributed public observation can support both scientific knowledge and local environmental awareness. eBird developed from a bird observation platform into a large-scale biodiversity data network used by researchers, conservation organisations and policy makers (Sullivan et al., 2009). Its value lies not only in the volume of data collected, but in the way ordinary birdwatchers are positioned as contributors to ecological knowledge production (Sullivan et al., 2009). Distributed observation is especially valuable for urban ecology because ecological data often depends on repeated, local and time-sensitive encounters.

Community benefit emerges when participation changes how residents notice and understand their surroundings. Bonney et al. argue that citizen science can expand scientific knowledge while also improving public scientific literacy (Bonney et al., 2009). Dickinson and Bonney frame citizen science as public participation in environmental research, where learning takes place through observation, contribution and feedback (Dickinson and Bonney, 2012). When residents record, identify or discuss ecological signals, they begin to attend to the environment differently. The environment is no longer a passive background; it becomes something that can be observed, interpreted and cared for.

Urban ecological processes often require this kind of situated attention because they are small-scale, temporary and easily overlooked. A bird call, a seasonal change, a patch of vegetation, a shift in air quality or a change in the local soundscape may not appear significant in isolation. Participatory sensing allows these weak signals to accumulate into a collective record of place. Individual observations may be modest, but they gain meaning when they are connected, compared and returned to the community through shared interfaces.

Recognition is one of the key community benefits of participatory ecological sensing. Environmental data systems often privilege expert knowledge, technical measurement and institutional authority. Participatory sensing can challenge this hierarchy by giving value to lived experience, subjective perception and local forms of attention. Gabrys argues that environmental sensing technologies do not simply measure the world; they participate in making environmental relations and publics (Gabrys, 2016). Community participation creates a public around environmental conditions: people do not only receive information, but become involved in noticing, naming and discussing what matters in their local environment.

Sound-based and image-based participation makes environmental knowledge more accessible because it allows residents to contribute through everyday acts of witnessing. A sound recording, photograph or short observation can capture a local environmental condition without requiring expert language. Hush City uses crowdsourced recordings, photographs and subjective evaluations to map everyday quiet areas in cities (Radicchi, 2017). The project treats citizens’ sensory experience as legitimate urban knowledge rather than secondary opinion, showing how community participation can identify environmental qualities that are difficult to capture through conventional indicators alone (Radicchi, 2017).

A community benefit perspective also helps avoid an extractive model of smart city participation. If residents only provide data to a system without receiving meaningful feedback, participation risks becoming unpaid data labour. Participatory design and citizen science literature emphasise that feedback, visibility and shared interpretation are important for sustaining engagement (Bonney et al., 2009; Dickinson and Bonney, 2012). Participation becomes beneficial when the interface returns something to the community: environmental awareness, recognition, local knowledge, collective memory or opportunities for care.

Participatory ecological sensing connects technical measurement with collective ecological attention. A local interface can make environmental signals visible, audible and discussable, but its public value depends on whether those signals become part of shared experience. The benefit is not only informational but relational. Residents may come to recognise the green wall, birds, sounds and surrounding micro-environment as part of a shared urban ecology. Community participation turns environmental sensing into a collective practice of noticing and care.

